Izzie and I couldn't believe it. It almost sounds like an implausible story of a lunatic. But we nodded as we said, "Oh yeah, obviously, it's true." I was used to worrying about aimlessness. Izzie was used to worrying about boredom. But not a soul on the continent seems to be resigned to this behaviour either way. They do all think it's rotten, but they wouldn't waste a second on it or bother admonishing. No one seemed to have anything logical to say about ambition; quite unpardonably, they were too bold. I realized what a frigging dullard I'd become - an old man!

Pierre Van den Berghe

There are few issues about which the scholastic literature is more inconclusive and deeply entrenched in classical traditions than that of violence. The generally pervasive assumption seems to be that Africans can only be violent when colonized. A recent essay by Henry Louis Gates, Jr. entitled My Jacob, My Esau: Shadows of Conflict in Black Skin/White Masks’ has rendered the debate deeper within the Continental tradition of elucidating facts.
